rilling down and resolving story arcs and other loose ends, might take a little more than two months, but I am hoping that the workflow will be by that point streamlined and take less time administratively. Around this time I think, if it is going well, we should start thinking about the accompanying book. Waiting till then will peak more interest and reach more players, but still be in the early stages (meaning that most people will still be engaging with this world). Perhaps it could come a little earlier, but I think time-wise there will be more time to write it in the summer. This also spreads out payment for me, which I like. Phase 4 (?): June/July Onwards If I am honest, I do not have a clear idea of what will happen after this initial period. It may be that the project is completely self-contained, and we find a way to archive it so that it does not require hundreds of active players to be fun for others (This is something that I think is key to the project as a whole). It may be that we continue to add content, in a way that extends the experience, or start something in the same universe but with an entirely different format and narrative. I’m not sure. I think my main opposition comes from the statement that after Phase 2 I will not have a lot of input, and therefore payment only needs to reflect 6 months work. - The initial phase will run to nearly this amount any way. - From what Alexis has said, most of the content creation and implementation will be by me alone, and so I will be doing this throughout every phase. - Any extension that takes place will require extra work. - I do understand that this is extending into an unknown. I believe that: a) payment needs to accurately reflect the amount of work over the amount of time I will be doing it. B) Make provisions for if things are delayed, work overruns, etc. With these factors in place, work can continue until the point that we reach that unknown, at which point a further contract can be drafted to cover