            <Title>Tarot Harp</Title>
            <Text>This is the instrument of the Eremite, rendered in a digital format. It is an “improvisational participation engine”, providing a way to play the music puzzles if one is not a musician. Description - It has the basic form of an autoharp, but it has been heavily modified. It is much larger, with ornate buttons and levers all over it. - It is battered, dirty, caulked in mud. - One panel is missing, exposing the inside of the body. Features - The harp is fully rotatable, and every angle may be seen. - If the players zoom in on the broken panel, they see a very small, ripped label that says “C.F. Zimmerman Shifter, 1886” - There is a ship at sea carved into one corner of the Harp. - There are two points of input; the chord buttons, and the strings. Pressing a chord button before pressing the strings changes their sound. There are 3 chord buttons, and 15 strings. - Both the chord buttons and the strings are labelled. The chord buttons are labelled: Crisis Road Stars And the strings are labelled: Sword Key Raven Lake Chest Monk Beast Hero Cloak Elder Castle Pipes Princess Pauper Blood - When initially discovered, the strings make a disonant, untuned sound, as if they have not been stored well for some time. However, if a player has a certain item in his inventory in the Office Content, is logged in, and accesses the harp, it plays properly, having been tuned and cleaned. - On the reverse of the harp is found a poem, written in the Eremite’s handwriting on the same parchment, and affixed with thick glue: I will scan, iron muscle I will guess, bowel rustle I will run, voice giver I will love, tune shiver I will jump, finger lover I will sing, hole mother I will tell, story seeker You will know, I weaker. - The harp is accompanied by a Widsith note: Artefact Report 98238923JJ:// Loss File Item 12 Argus: The Tarot Harp Scriber: T.W.A.I.N. One C.F. Zimmerman 1886 5-bar “Shifter” model autoharp. Miscellaneous elements damage, salt rot, abrasion consistent with ijolite erosion. Strings have not been replaced since manufacture. Customised with extended cavity, tuning schema and rear-sided paint palette built directly into back plate. Personal Notes: He seems to have customised the instrument for his own purposes: what do these demarcations on the notes and chord buttons signify? He calls it the Tarot Harp; figures here do not represent traditional tarot arcana.</Text>
        </Document>
