            <Text>Inspirations From History

- The Scold’s Bride - a way to inhibit and punish those who transgressed society. Usually women, he usurps this role, as he does with every other.
- Executioner - a state-appointed official who executed criminals and others, in an anonymous fashion. A provost, headsman or hangman denotes the type used - would the Eremite be a coughsman? They were shunned by their neighbours, usually gypsies (at least for the Ottomans) or a Scharfrichter (keen judge) who was aided by a roaring “lion” (a shouting assistant), and tasked with rubbish clearance and brandings. 
- Plague Doctor - a grotesque, long-nosed creature. He uses his stick as a pen, to keep him separate. No touching, wax overcoats.
- John Snow and William Farr - debaters against and for miasma as the main transmitter of disease. 
- A wandering journeyman - learning his craft on the road. Compagnons, jack and knaves.
- Hermits - he has his own version of vegetarianism, no need to keep clean, ornamental hermits in Victorian gardens

Why Does One Wear A Mask?

- To hide disfigurement, either to protect other people or the sensibilities of the wearer. 
- To make it difficult to talk, or express oneself. 
- To preserve the features of one who has passed, as a death mask. The Eremite is preserving the features of others, all those who went before him, built up on top of each other. 
- To appease gods and demons.
- To cause terror in others.
- To modify or transform yourself.
- To hide one’s features.

