His Relationship With The Town

- In the end, he becomes a clown, a clumsy, tragic-funny figure. 
- He goes to fight monsters in this place. 
- He does not pay back any of the “gifts” he is given. He perceives slights everywhere. 
- He sees them in terms of energy. Low output/input, high potential.
- What is his blaison populaire for the people in the town?
- With what does he try to pay them?
- Does he order the cleanup of the town? Later on?
- The townspeople do treat religion as a disease, as it becomes a way to transfer bad practice. It is a horizontal transmission, like scared pigeons around a room, as they cause each other to fly away with the proselytism and remembrance of the past. The children pass this onto their parents, in a way, learning more of the rituals that supposedly keep them alienated. However, the Eremite also transmits both a literal and figurative disease in his malpractice of anthropology - they come to imitate him, his ideas and his actions. This needs to be clear. Some of their practices are very beautiful and, as he discovered to his shame and chagrin, have a  secret purpose; they become talismanic of his guilt as the story progresses.  Even their river is like a meme, in a way, bringing ideas to them and them mostly being discarded. There are huge nets in the river that capture refuse. They never use this rubbish, only sort it. 
- Their reactions to him need to be more varied. 
- The audience gets to see them, in a privileged position, in between his sanctioned recordings. 
- Does he smuggle her out in his suitcase - or an even smaller space. 

Equipment

- He has a cambium - a humour whose vapours are inhaled.
- The Gas Mask - a hugely inflated head, with two tubes, one for speech and one for breath. It extends down his throat. If the glass in the eyeholes shatters, the wearer is blinded or killed. There are sponges at the end of each tube. This is his shield, protecting and proclaiming. 
- The tent that he wears as a cloak. It has rents in it, and he views stars differently each time.
- He comes with a warning, like nuclear waste - I am poisonous, bury me in rock. In all languages, or in pictograms.








